Problem: 81. Search in Rotated Sorted Array II

Approach:
1. If nums[mid] == target, return true.
2. If duplicates at both ends create ambiguity
   (nums[st] == nums[mid] == nums[end]),
   shrink the search space by moving both pointers.
3. Otherwise, identify the sorted half.
4. Check whether the target lies inside the sorted half.
5. Continue Binary Search.

Time Complexity:
Average Case : O(log n)
Worst Case   : O(n)

Space Complexity:
O(1)
*/

class Solution {
public:
    bool search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {

        int n = nums.size();

        int st = 0;
        int end = n - 1;

        while (st <= end) {

            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] == target)
                return true;

            // Remove duplicates from both ends
            if (nums[st] == nums[mid] && nums[mid] == nums[end]) {
                st++;
                end--;
            }

            // Left half is sorted
            else if (nums[mid] >= nums[st]) {

                if (target >= nums[st] && target < nums[mid]) {
                    end = mid - 1;
                } else {
                    st = mid + 1;
                }
            }

            // Right half is sorted
            else {

                if (target > nums[mid] && target <= nums[end]) {
                    st = mid + 1;
                } else {
                    end = mid - 1;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
};
/*
==========================================
My Misconceptions / Learnings
==========================================

1. Problem 81 is NOT a completely new problem.

It is simply Problem 33 + one extra condition to handle duplicates.

------------------------------------------

2. Why do we add this condition?

if(nums[st] == nums[mid] && nums[mid] == nums[end]){
    st++;
    end--;
}

Reason:

When st, mid, and end have the same value, we cannot determine
which half is sorted because duplicates hide the rotation point.

------------------------------------------

3. Why do we do st++ and end--?

We only remove duplicate values from both ends.

These duplicates do not provide any useful information, so removing
them helps eliminate the ambiguity without losing the target.

------------------------------------------

4. Why not do st = mid + 1 or end = mid - 1?

Because we don't know which half contains the target.

Jumping may skip the target completely.

Shrinking by one position is the safest option.

------------------------------------------

5. Time Complexity

Average Case : O(log n)
Worst Case   : O(n)

Reason:

When there are many duplicates, we may have to shrink the search
space one element at a time instead of cutting it in half.
*/
